#{\footnote 20074}
${\footnote Lucy - Visible}
+{\footnote 1}
K{\footnote Lucy - Visible;}
\pard \plain \brdrb \cf12 \fs24 \b
\{bmc IDF20074.bmp\} Lucy - Visible\par
\pard \plain \cf0 \fs20
{\uldb Lucy}{\v 20067}\par
\par
The \b \i Lucy - visible \i0 \b0 element represents the flag of Lucy's visibility. If Lucy is visible, her motion over the sheet is animated according to the definition of the Lucy {\uldb sprite's}{\v 20049} definition. Lucy's visibility being switched off, Lucy's motions over the sheet are executed immediately.\par
\par
The element of Lucy's visibility can be treated as a normal logic variable. By using it in a logic term it can be tested, if Lucy is visible. Under "visibility" is understood the possibility of doing animations of the Lucy sprite independently on whether Lucy is present in the sheet visible portion. By using the visibility element as a command its value may be set by means of a logic term, thus switching Lucy's visibility on or off. In case a preceding command to step or to shift to a specified coordinate has been given she will first finish the shift before the visibility can be switched on or off.\par
\page

#{\footnote 20080}
${\footnote Item in front of Lucy}
+{\footnote 1}
K{\footnote Item in front of Lucy;}
\pard \plain \brdrb \cf12 \fs24 \b
\{bmc IDF20080.bmp\} Item in front of Lucy\par
\pard \plain \cf0 \fs20
{\uldb Lucy}{\v 20067}\par
\par
The \b \i item in front of Lucy \i0 \b0 element represents an item on a square in front of Lucy. As a square in front of Lucy a square is considered that is located at a distance of one step from Lucy in the direction of her orientation. By redefining the Lucy sprite the number of orientations can be raised to 8, thus making the squares in the diagonal direction accessible, too.\par
\par
The element of the item in front of Lucy can be treated as a normal logic variable of an item. By using it in a term containing items the contents of the square in front of Lucy can be tested. If the square in front of Lucy is situated outside the sheet, the item of the {\uldb sheet border}{\v 20249} is returned. By using it as a command the item on the square in front of Lucy can be adjusted. In case a preceding command to step or to shift to a specified coordinate has been given Lucy will first finish the shift before the item change can be achieved.\par
\page

#{\footnote 20082}
${\footnote Horizontal position of Lucy}
+{\footnote 1}
K{\footnote Horizontal position of Lucy;}
\pard \plain \brdrb \cf12 \fs24 \b
\{bmc IDF20082.bmp\} Horizontal position of Lucy\par
\pard \plain \cf0 \fs20
{\uldb Lucy}{\v 20067}\par
\par
The \b \i horizontal position of Lucy \i0 \b0 element represents Lucy's coordinate in the horizontal direction on the sheet. The element can be treated as a normal numeric variable. By using it in a numeric term Lucy's present coordinate (changing during the shift to a new position) can be found out. By using the element as a command a new horizontal coordinate of Lucy can be set. If Lucy is not visible, she will shift to the new position immediately. If she is visible, she will start shifting in an animated condition according to the Lucy sprite definition. By doing this, she will not wait for completing the former shift; the shift will start immediately. The commands to change the horizontal and the vertical coordinates may be entered immediately one after another, thus accomplishing the shift to the destination position in the diagonal direction. If Lucy needs to be stopped, it may be done so by setting a new position to her current position (i.e. to assign the coordinates to themselves). Unlike in case of the command for executing a step it is now possible to shift Lucy even outside the sheet.\par
\page

